{
  "id": "trpc_trpc_7233",
  "repo_name": "trpc/trpc",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/trpc/trpc",
  "base_commit": "5b0a4378f4bc5613ffc499c4781c549570799fbd",
  "pr_number": 7233,
  "issue_number": 7209,
  "issue_title": "bug: httpBatchStreamLink loses buffered chunks on normal stream completion due to closeOrAbort using controller.error() instead of controller.close()",
  "issue_body": "### Provide environment information\n\n```\nSystem:\n  OS: macOS 26.2\n  CPU: (10) arm64 Apple M1 Max\n  Memory: 78.77 MB / 32.00 GB\n  Shell: 5.9 - /bin/zsh\nBinaries:\n  Node: 24.11.1\n  pnpm: 10.9.0\nnpmPackages:\n  @trpc/client: ^11.1.0 => 11.7.2\n  @trpc/server: ^11.1.0 => 11.7.2\n  @trpc/react-query: ^11.1.0 => 11.7.2\n  @tanstack/react-query: ^5.74.4 => 5.90.12\n  next: 15.2.8\n  react: ^19.0.1 => 19.2.1\n  typescript: ^5 => 5.9.3\n```\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nWhen using `httpBatchStreamLink`, **normal stream completion causes all buffered (enqueued but unconsumed) chunks in the `ReadableStream` to be silently discarded**. This is because `closeOrAbort` calls `cancelAll()` \u2192 `controller.error(reason)` for **both** the `close` and `abort` handlers of the `WritableStream`.\n\nPer the [WHATWG Streams specification](https://streams.spec.whatwg.org/#rs-error), `controller.error()` immediately transitions the stream to the `\"errored\"` state and **discards all enqueued chunks** in the internal queue. In contrast, `controller.close()` transitions to `\"closed\"` and allows the consumer to drain all remaining buffered data.\n\n#### Root cause\n\nIn [`src/unstable-core-do-not-import/stream/jsonl.ts`](https://github.com/trpc/trpc/blob/main/packages/server/src/unstable-core-do-not-import/stream/jsonl.ts):\n\n```typescript\n// Line 588-591\nconst closeOrAbort = (reason?: unknown) => {\n  headDeferred?.reject(reason);\n  streamManager.cancelAll(reason);  // \u2190 always calls controller.error()\n};\n\n// Line 615-616 \u2014 both handlers use the same function\nclose: closeOrAbort,\nabort: closeOrAbort,\n```\n\nAnd in `cancelAll`:\n\n```typescript\n// Line 484-488\nfunction cancelAll(reason: unknown) {\n  for (const controller of controllerMap.values()) {\n    controller.error(reason);  // \u2190 discards buffered chunks per WHATWG spec\n  }\n}\n```\n\nOn normal completion, the `WritableStream`'s `close` handler is called (not `abort`), meaning the server has successfully sent all data. However, `closeOrAbort` treats this identically to an abort \u2014 it calls `controller.error(undefined)`, which:\n\n1. Discards all chunks that were `enqueue()`d but not yet `read()` by the consumer\n2. Passes `undefined` as the error reason, which causes downstream issues (e.g., AI SDK's `makeRequest` catch block does `err.name` on `undefined`, throwing a `TypeError`)\n\n#### Impact\n\nThis creates a **race condition** between the producer (HTTP response \u2192 JSONL parser \u2192 `controller.enqueue()`) and the consumer (`ReadableStream` \u2192 application code). For long streaming responses (e.g., 1500+ chunks from an LLM), the producer often finishes writing all chunks before the consumer has read them all. When `close` fires, the remaining buffered chunks are lost.\n\n**Observed behavior:**\n- Short responses: usually works (consumer keeps up with producer)\n- Long responses: **truncated output** \u2014 the consumer receives only a portion of the data\n- The stream ends with `error(undefined)` instead of `close()`, so consumers cannot distinguish between a normal completion and an actual error\n\n#### WHATWG Streams spec reference\n\nFrom [\u00a74.7.3 ReadableStreamDefaultController.error()](https://streams.spec.whatwg.org/#rs-default-controller-error):\n\n> *\"The error(e) method will error the readable stream, making all future interactions with it fail with the given error e.\"*\n\nVerified empirically:\n\n```javascript\n// Demonstrates that controller.error() discards buffered chunks\nconst rs = new ReadableStream({\n  start(controller) {\n    controller.enqueue(\"chunk-1\");\n    controller.enqueue(\"chunk-2\");\n    controller.enqueue(\"chunk-3\");\n    controller.error(undefined);  // \u2190 all 3 chunks are lost\n  }\n});\nconst reader = rs.getReader();\nawait reader.read(); // throws undefined instead of returning chunk-1\n```\n\n```javascript\n// controller.close() allows draining all buffered chunks\nconst rs = new ReadableStream({\n  start(controller) {\n    controller.enqueue(\"chunk-1\");\n    controller.enqueue(\"chunk-2\");\n    controller.enqueue(\"chunk-3\");\n    controller.close();  // \u2190 chunks are preserved\n  }\n});\nconst reader = rs.getReader();\nawait reader.read(); // { value: \"chunk-1\", done: false }\nawait reader.read(); // { value: \"chunk-2\", done: false }\nawait reader.read(); // { value: \"chunk-3\", done: false }\nawait reader.read(); // { value: undefined, done: true }\n```\n\n### Suggested fix\n\nDifferentiate between `close` (normal completion) and `abort` (error) in the `WritableStream` handlers:\n\n```typescript\n// Option A: Separate close and abort handlers\nconst source = response.body!\n  .pipeThrough(/* ... */)\n  .pipeTo(\n    new WritableStream({\n      write(chunk) { /* ... */ },\n      close() {\n        // Normal completion: close all controllers (preserves buffered data)\n        for (const controller of controllerMap.values()) {\n          controller.close();\n        }\n      },\n      abort(reason) {\n        // Error/abort: error all controllers\n        headDeferred?.reject(reason);\n        streamManager.cancelAll(reason);\n      },\n    }),\n  );\n```\n\n```typescript\n// Option B: Minimal change \u2014 check if reason is provided\nconst closeOrAbort = (reason?: unknown) => {\n  headDeferred?.reject(reason);\n  if (reason !== undefined) {\n    streamManager.cancelAll(reason);\n  } else {\n    // Normal close \u2014 use controller.close() to preserve buffered data\n    for (const controller of controllerMap.values()) {\n      controller.close();\n    }\n  }\n};\n```\n\nOption A is preferred as it's more explicit and doesn't rely on `undefined` as a sentinel value.\n\n### Link to reproduction\n\n_No StackBlitz reproduction yet \u2014 the issue is observable in any setup where the consumer processes chunks slower than the producer enqueues them (e.g., streaming LLM responses via AI SDK `useChat` with `httpBatchStreamLink`)._\n\n### To reproduce\n\n1. Set up a tRPC streaming mutation that yields many chunks (e.g., 500+ text deltas from an LLM)\n2. Use `httpBatchStreamLink` on the client\n3. Consume the stream via `ReadableStream` (e.g., through AI SDK's `useChat` transport)\n4. Observe that for long responses, the output is **truncated** \u2014 the tail end of the stream is lost\n5. Verify in DevTools Network tab that the full response body was received (all chunks present in the HTTP response)\n\nThe race condition is timing-dependent: shorter responses may work fine because the consumer keeps up with the producer.\n\n### Additional information\n\n#### Workaround\n\nWe currently work around this by **eagerly draining** the `AsyncIterator` into a buffer before the `ReadableStream`'s `pull()` is called:\n\n```typescript\nfunction asyncIteratorToReadableStream<T>(\n  iterator: AsyncIterator<T>,\n  option?: { abortSignal?: AbortSignal },\n): ReadableStream<T> {\n  const buffer: T[] = [];\n  let isDrained = false;\n  let drainError: { value: unknown } | null = null;\n  let onBufferUpdate: (() => void) | null = null;\n\n  // Eagerly consume iterator in the background\n  void (async () => {\n    try {\n      while (!option?.abortSignal?.aborted) {\n        const result = await iterator.next();\n        if (result.done) break;\n        buffer.push(result.value);\n        onBufferUpdate?.();\n        onBufferUpdate = null;\n      }\n    } catch (error) {\n      if (error !== undefined) drainError = { value: error };\n    } finally {\n      isDrained = true;\n      onBufferUpdate?.();\n      onBufferUpdate = null;\n    }\n  })();\n\n  return new ReadableStream<T>({\n    async pull(controller) {\n      if (buffer.length > 0) {\n        controller.enqueue(buffer.shift()!);\n        return;\n      }\n      if (!isDrained) {\n        await new Promise<void>((r) => { onBufferUpdate = r; });\n        if (buffer.length > 0) {\n          controller.enqueue(buffer.shift()!);\n          return;\n        }\n      }\n      if (drainError) controller.error(drainError.value);\n      else controller.close();\n    },\n  });\n}\n```\n\nThis decouples our consumer from the tRPC-managed `ReadableStreamDefaultController`, ensuring all chunks are captured before tRPC can discard them.\n\n#### Related issue\n\n- #6996 (different bug \u2014 JSON parse errors in React Native streaming, but also related to `httpBatchStreamLink` reliability)\n- #6103 (AI SDK + tRPC integration discussion)\n\n### \ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc67\u200d\ud83d\udc66 Contributing\n\n- [x] \ud83d\ude4b\u200d\u2642\ufe0f Yes, I'd be down to file a PR fixing this bug!",
